msContents.summary: This is an Italian manuscript from the first half of the fifteenth century, which contains many texts that can be divided into five sections: an opening fragment from Giovanni da Calvoli's Meditations on the Life of Christ; a small group of texts by early Christian writers on the hagiography of Saint Jerome; a large group of letters by Saint Jerome, some spurious; a small group of works attributed to Seneca or Pseudo-Seneca; sermons of Franciscus de Mayronis. These are followed by a short group of precepts for all Christians. It is supposed that the manuscript was probably copied in a Franciscan environment and, although none of the texts is rare, the compilation is unusual and rarely brought together in this fashion.

history.provenance: Probably copied in a Franciscan environment (because of the particular combination of texts), and most likely in central Italy (on the basis of the script and the delicate penwork decoration); unidentified erased stamp on first folio of first quire containing table of contents; Howard Lehman Goodhart Memorial Fund
